segments.text: This is an interview with Dr. Judith Baer by John Zaloom on May 1, 1991, at Bolton Hall, and it's concerning the student movement of the 60s.
First, I want to ask how you would describe the situation of the students at Bryn Mawr when you were there as compared to how it may have been before that time and might have been after it.
I think I have a very good perspective.
I arrived there in 63.
I took a year off.
So I didn't graduate until 1968, and it seems to me to have changed extraordinarily in those times.
And essentially, in 1963, you still had, now remember this was an elite women's college,
You had very hardworking, very docile, very unquestioning students.
And most of them were perfectly happy with the assumption that they would spend four years working like hell and be involved in the intellectual riches of an education there.
And then they would get married and become suburban housewives.
That was the mindset.
Bryn Mawr has always
graduated intellectuals.
It has graduated professors.
It graduated Katherine Hepburn, who certainly was not your typical 1930s housewife.
It's always had room for brilliant eccentrics of that sort.
But that was not the norm.
You'd go to class, and the professor would lecture, and people would sit there.
And I became famous in my philosophy class for raising questions.
I don't think the professor minded because he was new, but I think the students really did because some people wouldn't even knit in class.
The year before I went there, Mademoiselle, which at that time was running a series about colleges, had an article in Bryn Mawr, and they were talking about knitting in class, and they interviewed
one English teacher who said, I always think I've succeeded in class if I've made it difficult for them to get through that complicated Swedish bit at the shoulder.
That was about how it was.
And then by the time 68 rolled around and I was graduating, I had changed my professional goals from law school to political science.
I had this wonderful political science professor who was my
the director of my honors thesis, and we had wonderful classes and always very disputatious, and he refused to teach the class in the usual lecture mode.
We had student radicals all over the place.
We had people who had been arrested in civil rights demonstrations who were active in SDS.
The editor of the student newspaper the year I graduated was a radical and
her roommate, who was a junior, was elected president of the Self-Government Association for the next year, which was amazing.
Because for years, self-government's role had been to rubber-stamp the administration.

I didn't know this until very recently, but there's a letter, an anonymous letter in the current issue of my alumni bulletin from a member of my original class, class of 67, who was kicked out, was expelled by the decision of the self-government honor board because she got married, and the reason she got married was that she was pregnant.
Now, I mean, this is just amazing.
now that anything like that could happen.
But that's essentially what happened to her.
And that certainly was not happening anymore.
And the administration was very conservative, although they were...
It was an interesting thing because Bryn Mawr was a college established by the Society of Friends, the Quakers, like Swarthmore and Haverford, who were its neighbors.
And I never understood how the college had
totally absorbed Quaker attitudes in terms of social behavior, which are very conservative.
Quakers typically do not drink.
They do not forbid it, but they tend to question it.
We could not have liquor on campus.
Quakers did not, at that time, approve of extramarital sex.
were very limited in the number of hours that men could be in our rooms or that we could stay out overnight.
We had sign-outs and we had hours that we had to be in, parietal hours and all of those things.
I mean, there was no rule against sex because that was too difficult a subject to mention.
It was the kind of thing that was considered bringing discredit on the college.
So those ideas were absorbed from the Quakers.
The Quaker tradition of activism was not.

Activities like getting arrested for civil rights demonstrations or protesting against the war were not an honored part of the Bryn Mawr tradition, although they very much were an honored part of the Quaker tradition.
And you had this administration that I think was composed of people that a hundred years before that would have been called blue stockings, women intellectuals.
And they were very much in favor of deviating from the norm in terms of having a career and being a scholar.
and you didn't have to get married and have kids.
But they were not in favor of deviating from the norm in terms of social protest.
That was a very frightening thing for them.

And there was this kind of war between the administration and many of the students, and certainly the student leaders, which was going on during the year at the end of the time, 67 and 68, that I was there.
OK. My next question you seem to have covered a little bit.
I was going to ask if the phenomena
in loco parentis was prevalent at Bryn Mawr.
Oh, was it ever.
And what the rules and regulations might have been.
You seem to have covered a couple of them.
Now, the rules and regulations were much more lenient than they were at most places.
And, you know, we used to joke, you know, and in loco parentis means it means crazy like parents.
But, for example, you could stay out until 1030 at night.
without signing up.

You could have an unlimited number of sign outs, and it was, let's see, it was 1230 on weekdays, 2 a.m. on weekends, and if you were going someplace, oh, for example, if you went to a play in Philadelphia, you could get a 130 sign out on weekends because you wouldn't be back.
until that late.
And you could, unless you got on probation, you could have as many of these as you wanted and you simply had to sign out, say, where you were going.
For overnights,
You could essentially go anywhere you wanted except to a guy's dorm.
You could go to somebody's apartment.
You could sign up as care of last name, 1500 Broad Street, Philadelphia.
They didn't care that it was your boyfriend.
They wouldn't check up on you.
That was perfectly all right.
But you did have to sign up.
They did have to know where you were, which I think now we would see a violation of privacy.
As for parietal hours, as I recall,
When I first got there, men could be in your rooms until 630, and then they could be in the public parts of the dormitories, the smokers, and so on.
That was another thing.
It was assumed that all adults smoked at that time, until 1030.
And by the time I graduated, I think men could be in your rooms until 1030.
So they had changed.
And these, compared to what happened for most, not only for women's colleges, but for women,
in coed colleges during the 60s, those were very, very liberal regulations.
But they did exist, and they became a controversy, and eventually all sign outs were abolished.
Now, as I recall, that didn't happen until I had left, but it was a really, it was a very, very passionately fought and controversial issue during the time I was there.
Did you perceive that many other changes occurred during just the years that you were there in the rules and regulations?
Yes.
There were the changes and the relaxation on the way to abolition of the sign-out rules and parietal rules.
And by the way, now they have co-ed dorms.
The rules, the dress rules.
For example, you had to wear skirts at classes.
You had to wear skirts at dinner.
All of that were changed.
And I think the year after I graduated, they were totally abolished.
Other than that,
Most of the big changes came after I'd left.
But there was certainly, I mean, it was clear by the time I graduated that the sign-outs were going to go.
The parietal rules were going to go.
They had already been considerably relaxed.
As far as the student movement, first, if you might define it in your terms, what do you think the movement means?
And secondly, tell me about when you became involved in it.
Well, I think of the student movement as actually involving student power, issues of student governance.
And I think that you'd have to say that it probably began, had begun, by 1968.
And I certainly got involved in it

Oh, well, earlier than that, I was involved in the time I got back from my year away, which was January of 1967, insofar as the movement was concentrated on changing pariah rules, dress rules, sign-out rules, all of those things, getting student governments over one's own life.
Later on, the focus broadened very much.
I mean, when I got to Chicago,
As a graduate student, of course, I had all the freedom I wanted.
Even the Graduate Women's Dormitory didn't have those rules.
Then, all of a sudden, the issue was participating in faculty decision-making, which concerned you.
And I was involved from the very beginning.
My second quarter there, January of 1969, it was announced that a very popular radical feminist assistant professor in sociology, Marlene Dixon, would not be rehired.
And the result of that was a student sit-in, was all kinds of things.
Mrs. Dixon wasn't rehired.
She got a year's reappointment, which she would not ordinarily have gotten.
She went on to McGill University.
And in fact, I really think I have to say that that part of the student movement failed.
Students did not.
win the power to participate in important decisions.
Now, they do sit on committees in most universities, including A&M, but they do not have any voice in tenure decisions and hiring decisions.
I think they should.
I think they're an important constituency.
My views on that have not changed.
But students do not have that participation.
It would seem that the only victory that has been gained is student evaluations.
Well, big deal, yeah.
You have an input.
in terms of that.
And by the way, most large universities like A&M, which are research-oriented, that's going to be a negative input rather than a positive input.
People can get fired for bad teaching.
They will not get kept on because of good teaching alone.
Now, in the liberal arts colleges which emphasize teaching, that may not be true.
But it is certainly true in the major universities.
I have to say that the success of the student movement has been mixed as far as victory over sign-out hours, parietal hours, which didn't affect men anyway in most places, or didn't govern them.
You have that as far as participation in academic governance.
Governance, you don't have that to any meaningful extent.
Was there
a strong anti-war feeling at Bryn Mawr?
Oh, boy.
It was there ever.
And Bryn Mawr went through the same metamorphosis that society did.
By the beginning of, in the time that, 64, 65, the first years I was there, the anti-war sentiment was very much a minority on campus.
You had a very large apathetic middle, and you had some people who supported the war essentially because they supported whatever
The government did.
I mean, this was what you had been brought up to do.
And by the end of the 60s, the majority of the students were against the war.
Absolutely.
Now, they were against this particular war, the war in Vietnam.
They were not pacifists, most of them.
They were not necessarily advocates of a ban on nuclear testing.
I don't think that issue came up.
But certainly, the anti-Vietnam sentiment changed, as it did in the country.
probably a little ahead of the other country.
Were you first involved in the movement in general and then specifically more into the women's movement?
I got involved through civil rights to anti-war to student to feminist and that was essentially my trajectory.
There was no
feminist, obvious, real, powerful, feminist presence at Bryn Mawr when I graduated.
There would be in another couple of years, but not in 1968.
And, in fact, you really can say that the women's movement, you almost have to say, you can almost put a year to its beginning in that 68, 69.
Now, obviously, there were four, there were
for earlier impetuses like Betty Friedan's book, The Feminine Mystique, in 63.
But it was amazing.
When I left Bryn Mawr in 68, there was no feminist movement.
All of a sudden, in Chicago, in 69, there was.
And it was like that.
It was incredible how fast this particular mobilization happened.
Do you feel that that was because you went to Chicago or because it was the time period?
I think it was the time period.

Chicago was by no means unique, and by the time within two years that I had left Bryn Mawr in the fall of 1970, Kate Millett, who was the author of Feminist Politics, had been hired to teach a course there for one semester.
That was how quickly this happened.
How involved were you with the movement at Chicago as opposed to Bryn Mawr, and what types of demonstrations did you attend there?
OK, do you mean the feminist movement or the student movement?
Any aspect of it.
OK.
I think at the beginning I was just as much involved with student and peace movements generally, more with feminist movements, because of course there hadn't been any.
By the end of the time I was at Chicago, which was 1974, less involved, partly because writing a dissertation is really something that you
have to focus on, partly because there was less going on.
Let's see, I've demonstrations, now I wasn't in the sit-in, but I attended a lot of the demonstrations which focused on the Marlene Dixon case in 1969.
I attended the

Chicago demonstrations which centered around Nixon's invasion of Cambodia or, as we now know, Nixon's announcement of what essentially was, you know, he'd been bombing Cambodia for quite a while in spring of 1970 and the murder of students at Kent State and Jackson State.
There was also
Let's see, I didn't go to any demonstrations in Washington after I moved to Chicago.
So let's see, there was supportive demonstrations.
There always are.
If there's a big demonstration in Washington or New York, there are going to be supportive demonstrations in places like Chicago.
There was the moratorium, the two moratoriums, October and November of 69, the big demonstration in May of 1971, echoing the demonstration in Washington
Let's see.
Oh, there was in April 5, 1969, there was a big march, I think nationwide demonstrations.
I attended the one in Chicago.
In the summer of 1970, August 26, which is the anniversary of the ratification of the 19th Amendment, there was a huge feminist demonstration all over the country.
I attended the one in Chicago.
And let's see.
I think after 1971 there wasn't much.
That was really the kind of ending of demonstrations.
I see.

Since you finished your formal education in 1974, have you still been actively involved with the demonstrations or meetings dealing with women's equality in general or in which you specifically address the issue?
Oh, yeah.
I've made a memory now off and on.
In fact, I'm officially a member of the
Brazos County chapter, we just don't have much of a chapter.
Now, actually, I've been an active NOW member.
I've been a NOW member since 1976, National Organization for Women.
I've been to pro-choice demonstrations.
I remember particularly one in Los Angeles in March 1986 because it was pouring rain.
And then there was one in November of 89 at the Capitol in Austin.
I was at that.
So I continue to be involved, and I think as for many people, my involvement has taken a different kind of stance.
There just aren't that many demonstrations anymore.
But now I get involved, I think, more in my scholarship, which is feminist-oriented, than I do in local activism.
With some people, there is more local activism.
From your resume, it is apparent that a lot of your scholarship works deal with questions of equality under the law, especially for women.
Do you feel that your interest in these types of issues stems from being a student in the late 1960s and early 70s?
It goes back before that.
I think that my student activism stems from my
own consciousness of two things.
I mean, now, we all have a family joke that I've been a feminist ever since I could read.
And you've got to remember that we're talking the 50s, you know, June Cleaver, the feminine mystique.
And this occurred to me as a life I did not want to live.
And later on, no, I can remember the summer I was 10 making a decision that I did not want to grow up to live the life my mother did and the other women in our neighborhood.
And it was quite a conscious decision.
I didn't realize then that I needn't have worried.
But there it was.
And that was roughly the same time as the Civil Rights Movement was getting re-energized after the Brown decision.
And I was very sympathetic to this.

And both my own feminist consciousness, although we didn't really have that word then, except as an epithet, and my awareness of civil rights were what basically impelled me into the student movement.
And that force also got me involved in the feminist movement and feminist writings.
I think the way that I'm different from many 60s radicals, I don't know how many, but at least from the media prototype of the 60s radical, is that for me that has not changed.
I haven't gone and voted for Reagan and joined the capitalist majority and all that.
Many of them have.
What do you feel are the legacies of the student movement in which you participated, and where does the issue of equality for women stand today?
Certainly one legacy of the student movement is increased student control over their own lives.
You don't realize how parental it was 25 or 30 years ago.
Another legacy is the ability
and the assumption of the right to question governmental decisions.

I think we tend to forget that the vote in Congress on January 12th to get involved in the Gulf was a very mixed vote, and this is something that just did not happen in the early and middle years of the Vietnam War.
I think we have forgotten this has all been buried in the euphoria after the victory, but we do see
the assumption of a right on the part of individuals, on the part of other politicians, to question governmental decisions, particularly about war.
I think you've got to see a legacy.
The feminist legacy is very strong.
You consider almost half of the medical students and law students in this country today are women.
In graduate schools, the numbers are lower in most disciplines, but they're still a lot higher than they were 20 or 25
years ago.
Very important gains have been won.
There have been changes in laws.
One important example is just the extraordinary changes in rape laws.
The focus, with a few very bizarre cases,
to the contrary, which get a lot of publicity, there is more focus on perpetrators and less focus on victims.
There are changes in the way that graduate fellowships and things like that are awarded.
There are changes in hiring.
I mean, it used to be 30 years ago, a law firm or the State Department or an academic department could say, we don't hire women.
If a woman
took the oral examination in the State Department to become a foreign service officer 30 years ago.
Her score, an automatic either 5 points or 10 points was deducted from her score just for being a woman.
You don't see that anymore.
I see a great deal that still needs to be done.
There is the phenomenon of the glass ceiling.
I mean, you see it if you compare the percentage of women associate professors at A&M to women full professors.
You see it in business and law firms.
Women don't seem to get promoted to the higher ranks.
One thing that has not changed is women's hugely disproportionate share of family responsibilities for children, for housework, for parents as they age, and so on.
We've all heard discussions about the mommy track, which is a very controversial proposal.
But the whole idea, that couldn't even have happened except for the fact that
There is this load of responsibility that women have that men don't.
To achieve real equality, that's got to change.
And I don't see that happening anytime soon.
Do you feel like the future holds much positive for women's equality?
Yes, I think there are positive prospects.
Certainly you've got to say that there are gains.
There are going to be women
who eventually are going to move into top positions because of the fact that, well, just simply that not all women have families.
And those that have children are having fewer children.
Those that marry are marrying later and are more apt to get divorced.
There are going to be women with lots of years left who are professional, with lots of time to devote to advancement.
That's going to be positive.
However,
Economic recessions are very bad.
We have one now.
We're always going to have some.
Women are going to tend to, in what were formerly male positions, are going to tend to be the last hired and the first fired.
That's not only true in professional positions, in higher paying blue collar positions.
One very positive sign
is the Supreme Court's decision in Johnson Controls that you can't keep women out of positions because they're involved with chemicals likely to harm a fetus.
And this was used against all women of childbearing age.
And one company defined childbearing age as beginning at 5 and ending at 63, if you can believe.
That's a very positive decision, particularly for working class women.
there is a possibility of eventually getting enacted the kind of bills that Bush has been vetoing, the family leave, the civil rights bills, the child care, all of those.
Those will help women very much.
I was reading today that you've
In the New York Times article, you find people like Phyllis Schlafly, the old anti-ERA person, and Pat Schroeder in Congress on the same side in some of these issues, which is rather unusual.
And if that is done, I see a lot in positive.
If it is positive, however, what we have now and what we are likely to have in 92, the best possible solution is a stalemate of Republican president and Democratic Congress.
It is possible that you're going to have one or both houses of Congress Republican.
I don't think it's going to happen.
It could.
If that is true, the chances of change are even less.
The big problem is you can do all you want with the government.
There is not going to be equality until the behavior of individual men and women in families change.
And that's something that's going to take generations.
So if you give me 1,000 years to predict into the future, I'm optimistic.
In the short run, I'm less so.
Well, I really appreciate this interview.
I enjoyed it.
Thank you.
